[1
Date: 25 August 2000
From: A. Vladyko <ata@briem.ac.by>
ProMED-mail Regional Moderator for NIS/CIS
Source: Official Information from the Health Ministry of the Russian
Federation, (Outbreaks News Website, in Russian) 9 Aug 2000 [edited
<http://www.depart.drugreg.ru/hotline/index.html>

Outbreak of enteroviral meningitis in Komsomolsk-on-the-Amur
-----------------------------------------------------------
A seasonal outbreak of enteroviral meningitis morbidity has been [recorded
in the period from 21 Jun to 8 Aug 2000 in the city of the
Komsomolsk-on-the-Amur, Khabarovsk Province (Oblast). A total of 335
children (all under 14 years old) were involved, 228 of them between 3 and
11 years of age. At the present time 120 children are hospitalized, 75% of
whom have a serologically confirmed diagnosis. Echovirus type 17
[ECHO-17 has been isolated [from these patients. This enterovirus has
been the predominant serotype associated with enteroviral meningitis [in
recent years. The disease has taken a mild to moderately serious course
without complications. The outbreak has [affected two regions of the city:
from 21 June it was reported from the Leninsk area, then from 7 July in the
Central area.
Specialists from the Center of the State Sanitary-Epidemiological
Surveillance in the Khabarovsk Region stated that the outbreak has
[exhibited a contact-domestic route of disease transmission, [centering
on children's establishments. [Measures have been implemented to contain
the outbreak. A regime of damp clearing with use a chlorine preparations
has been instituted at the children's establishments, and swimming pools
have been closed to facilitate disinfection. Specimens from infected
patients, children in contact with the patients, drinking and sewage water
are being collected to monitor the outbreak.
*********
[2
Date: Fri 25 Aug 2000
Source: ITAR/TASS News Agency, 22 Aug 2000
Progress of the Komsomolsk-on-the-Amur enteroviral meningitis outbreak
---------------------------------------------------------------------
At the present time [Aug 25 142 children are hospitalized in the city of
Komsomolsk-on-the-Amur, 134 from them have a confirmed diagnosis of
enteroviral meningitis. Since the beginning of the outbreak (more than 8
weeks ago) a total of 336 children have recovered from infection. [Today a
further 11 children have been admitted to hospital; evidence of continued
active viral circulation.
The local [public health service intend to stop the infection by mass
immunization. Vaccination against poliomyelitis will be carried out during
1-2 days among 95% children attending junior schools. The adequate [amount
of vaccine has been sent to the city. Rita Liberova, chief public health
physician of the area, stated that during the next days [advice from the
Russian Ministry of Health [on vaccination procedure would be received.
It is predicted that the spread of infection should cease 8-10 days after
vaccination.
--
